      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nIn our games so far, we have been studying according to a logic in which something happened before, allowing new knowledge to emerge afterward. Let's do a quick review:\n- We saw that voice is not exclusive to our species, *Homo sapiens*. However, articulated speech is something that sets us apart from other animals close to us. In this text, we also learned that counting can be associated with our body (<htcite0>).\n- Next, we saw that different animals are known to have existed before us and that walked—or still walk—on Earth. In common, we all belong to a single genus, *Homo*. We also saw, in another stage of mathematical learning, that counting is present in our feet (<htcite1>).\n- In the game before this one, we were also introduced to DNA and the fact that it is responsible for the transmission of heredity, which allows us to find relationships between ourselves and the ancient skeletons—known as fossils—that we find. Connecting the knowledge acquired in previous games, we also saw that it is possible to add using our body (<htcite2>).\n\nSince the changes that lead to the emergence of a species occur constantly from one generation to the next, until new species appear, it is inevitable that questions about earlier species will arise. So, let us begin with an initial reflection:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "80ae0cca-8a79-4be3-a359-f1dd8700110b",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Hands and Music",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "cd150cb3-20bf-46c2-9327-10a39373e9da",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Walking and Singing",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "8b947b40-dc98-4991-924d-d4356a0f55a8",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Exercising with Music",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Between us and them</b><br /><br />We are <i>Homo Sapiens</i> and currently inhabit the entire planet. However, we were not the first to spread across the planet.<br /><br /><i>Homo neanderthalensis</i>, which inhabited Europe and Asia and is very close to us, also lived in Europe and parts of Asia (<htcite0>).<br /><br />What would be the closest animal between us and them?</div></div></center>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ab1dda1e-95c2-4087-8299-e851e58bdc6f",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Humans",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_heidelbergensis",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### A common relative\n\nBetween <htdate0> and <htdate1>, another species of the genus *Homo* very close to us inhabited the Earth: *Homo heidelbergensis* (**Figure 1**) (<htcite0>; <htcite1>; <htcite2>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "75d196c9-1c1e-4106-bef5-ce8558d00d31",
                     "text": "Tattersall, I., & Schwartz, J. H.",
                     "page": "pp. 77",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2010",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "344b68b3-9002-4857-8e6f-21f2114ae462",
                     "text": "Dorey, Fran",
                     "page": "Homo heidelbergensis",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2021",
                        "month": "6",
                        "day": "28"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ab1dda1e-95c2-4087-8299-e851e58bdc6f",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Humanos",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "-600000",
                     "month": "",
                     "day": ""
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "-300000",
                     "month": "",
                     "day": ""
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgHer\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgHer', '0%')\" src=\"images/DonsMaps/1590b.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\" style=\"width: 42%\"/></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Figure 1</b>: <i>Homo heidelbergensis</i> fossil. © Don Hitchcock. Original en el <i>Western Australian Museum</i> (<htcite0>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "13d45cd2-03d0-4e7b-aa62-9e61e6275236",
                     "text": "Hitchcock, Don",
                     "page": "Homo heidelbergensis",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2013",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The period in which *Homo heidelbergensis* lived leads researchers such as Fran Dorey from the Australian Museum to draw our attention to the possibility of a relationship between us and other species of the genus *Homo* (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "344b68b3-9002-4857-8e6f-21f2114ae462",
                     "text": "Dorey, Fran",
                     "page": "Homo heidelbergensis",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2021",
                        "month": "6",
                        "day": "28"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><ul class=\"citation\"> <li><i><i>Homo heidelbergensis</i> began to develop regional differences that eventually gave rise to two species of humans. European populations of <i>Homo heidelbergensis</i> evolved into <i>Homo neanderthalensis</i> (the Neanderthals) while a separate population of <i>Homo heidelbergensis</i> in Africa evolved into our own species, <i>Homo sapiens</i>.</i></li></ul></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "In addition to the temporal factor, we would also like to highlight brain size, compatible with our own, which would justify this proximity between us, Neanderthals (**Figure 2**), and this species (<htcite0>).\n\nBefore moving on to mathematics practice, we would like to emphasize that this conclusion is not shared by all the publications studied for content production at History Tracers. There are also researchers who defend the existence of a common ancestor between us (*Homo sapiens*), rather than *Homo heidelbergensis* being the common ancestor (<htcite1>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "75d196c9-1c1e-4106-bef5-ce8558d00d31",
                     "text": "Tattersall, I., & Schwartz, J. H.",
                     "page": "pp. 77",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2010",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "7fa66cfd-dca8-4a17-bead-e79954ba684a",
                     "text": "Wood, B., & Collard, M.",
                     "page": "pp. 68",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1999",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"book_navigation\"><tr><td><i>Homo neanderthalensis</i></td><td><i>Homo sapiens</i></td></tr><tr><td><img id=\"imgNean\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgNean', '0%')\" src=\"images/DonsMaps/img_6801ferrassie.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\" style=\"width: 20%\"/></td><td><img id=\"imgHs7\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgHs7', '0%')\" src=\"images/MexicoCityMuseo/HomoSapiens.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%;\"/></td></tr></table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Figure 18</b>: Fossil of <i>Homo neanderthalensis</i> on the left. © Don Hitchcock. Original at the <i>Vienna Natural History Museum, Naturhistorisches Museum Wien</i> (<htcite0>). Poster of the human skeleton describing <i>Homo sapiens</i> on the right. At the Museo Nacional de Antropología in México (<htcite1>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "4c4ac42b-d2a9-45e9-ab2c-3420e19be902",
                     "text": "Hitchcock, Don",
                     "page": "La Ferrassie Cave or Abri - a Neanderthal rock shelter",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2015",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0be2ea18-ab78-4cb1-b3be-1ff0ba4ade95",
                     "text": "Museo Nacional de Antropologia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "### The Game\n\nEvolution occurs because populations of different living beings have new generations, meaning they are multiplying. Therefore, to understand why we are here and what the next generations might be like, we need to master multiplication.\n\nIn this game, a calculation already learned in previous texts will be presented. To reinforce your knowledge, perform the operation by moving your limbs (hands and feet), as suggested.\n\n#### Rules\n\nThe game presents a calculation to be performed with your body. To start the calculation, click on the link (<i class=\"fa-solid fa-play\" style=\"font-size:1em;color:#0f0;\" ></i>). If you want to repeat it for reinforcement, click again.\n\nTo perform a new calculation, click on (<i class=\"fa-solid fa-chevron-right\"></i>).\n\nYou can also choose a single multiplication table or let the system choose one randomly in the **Multiplication table** field.\n\nThe main goal of the game is to reinforce that multiplication consists of repeated additions of the same quantity (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eaa59295-fb80-4c33-b1e4-bcdf3c11dabf",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Adding the same numbers",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "5",
                        "day": "9"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"text-align=center\"><center>&nbsp;<span id=\"nextVal\"></span>&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span id=\"topVal\"></span><br />×&nbsp;&nbsp;<span id=\"bottomVal\"></span><br />____________<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;<span id=\"resVal\"></span></center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 1</b>: Sum of the values to be performed with the body.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"speed-control\"><b>Multiplication Table:</b> <select id=\"mtValues\"><option value=\"-1\">Ramdomly</option></select> <label>Slow</label> <input type=\"range\" id=\"speedSlider\" min=\"600\" max=\"1600\" value=\"1100\" step=\"10\" style=\"direction: rtl;\"> <label>Fast</label>  <i class=\"fa-solid fa-play\" onclick=\"htExecuteMult();\" style=\"font-size:2em;color:#0f0;\" ></i> <i class=\"fa-solid fa-chevron-right\"  onclick=\"htNewLocalMultiplication();\" style=\"font-size:2em;\"></i></div> <div class=\"counters\"> <b>Current Number</b><span id=\"clapCounter\" class=\"counter\">: 0</span><input type=\"hidden\" id=\"handPosCounter\" /> <input type=\"hidden\" id=\"clapCount\" value=\"0\" /></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
